---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="AI Workflow Design & Execution Checklist — AI Agent Puzzle"
  description="A checklist to walk through before running any AI workflow: task goal, data source, steps, tools, output format, stop conditions, human review, modification scope, privacy, and result verification. Once the task is split clearly, AI can help inside a safe, checkable boundary."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container ai-agent-checklist">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">A Checklist to Run Through Before Any AI Workflow</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          We've already practiced several AI workflows: organizing CSV and tabular data, creating and updating tasks via the Notion API, and turning an article into reading notes, an outline, and a draft revision. The tasks look different on the surface, but they share one principle: <strong>don't ask the AI to do the whole thing in one shot</strong>.
        </p>
      </header>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        A more reliable approach is:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>First confirm the <strong>goal</strong></li>
        <li>Then confirm the <strong>data source</strong></li>
        <li>Then split into <strong>steps</strong></li>
        <li>Then decide <strong>where tools are needed</strong></li>
        <li>Finally, <strong>check the result</strong> and keep human review in place</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This page isn't building a new tool — it's putting together an "<strong>AI workflow checklist</strong>." From now on, whenever you ask AI to organize data, write drafts, drive Notion, read files, or call an API, you can run through this list once first.
      </p>

      <h2 class="detail-heading">Why bother with a checklist?</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Many AI failures <strong>aren't broken tools</strong> — they're tasks that weren't stated clearly enough up front:
      </p>

      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li>The <strong>data source</strong> wasn't named</li>
        <li>The <strong>output format</strong> wasn't specified</li>
        <li>What's <strong>off-limits</strong> wasn't stated</li>
        <li>What to do <strong>on failure</strong> wasn't stated</li>
        <li>Whether the result <strong>needs human review</strong> wasn't stated</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        In those cases the AI may quietly fill in the blanks. But what it fills in <strong>isn't necessarily true, and isn't necessarily what we wanted</strong>.
      </p>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          The point of a checklist: <strong>make the workflow clearer, safer, and easier to audit later</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ Quick Checklist ============ -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Quick checklist (when time is short)</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Before any AI workflow, run through these 8 questions:
      </p>

      <div class="checklist-group">
        <ul class="checklist-group__list">
          <li>Did I <strong>state the task goal</strong> clearly?</li>
          <li>Did I <strong>provide the data source</strong>?</li>
          <li>Did I tell the AI <strong>which data it can rely on</strong>?</li>
          <li>Did I <strong>split the task into steps</strong>?</li>
          <li>Did I <strong>specify the output format</strong>?</li>
          <li>Did I say <strong>when to stop</strong>?</li>
          <li>Did I name what <strong>needs human review</strong>?</li>
          <li>Did I <strong>verify the final result</strong>?</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="callout-card callout-card--warn">
        <p class="callout-text">
          If several of these have no clear answer, the task <strong>isn't ready to be handed to the AI yet</strong>. Sort the brief out first — it's almost always smoother that way.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ PART 1 ============ -->
      <div class="part-divider">
        <span class="part-label">PART 1</span>
        <span class="part-text">10 detailed checks</span>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Each item expands into more detail, with self-check questions and example phrasings.
      </p>

      <!-- Item 1 -->
      <details class="details-card details-card--num">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__num">1</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Is the task goal clear?</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            First check: <strong>what's this workflow ultimately supposed to produce</strong>? Don't just say "help me handle this data" — too vague. The AI doesn't know whether you want a count, summary, check, classification, or a draft.
          </p>

          <div class="compare-pair">
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">A clearer phrasing</span>
              <p>Based on this CSV, organize event sign-up counts, identify people whose diet field is blank, and finally produce a draft event reminder.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            Now the AI knows the endpoint: <strong>tally counts → flag issues → produce reminder draft</strong>.
          </p>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Self-check questions</h4>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>What <strong>result</strong> do I want?</li>
            <li>Is it a <strong>table, list, summary, or draft</strong>?</li>
            <li>Am I asking it to <strong>organize data, or perform an action</strong>?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Item 2 -->
      <details class="details-card details-card--num">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__num">2</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Is the data source explicit?</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            When the AI answers, it should know <strong>what data it's grounded in</strong>. The source might be:
          </p>

          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>A CSV file</li>
            <li>A Notion database</li>
            <li>An article file</li>
            <li>An assignment specification</li>
            <li>An API response</li>
            <li>A piece of text the user supplied</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            If the source isn't stated, the AI may fall back on its own background knowledge — which goes wrong fast when you're handling data, reports, tasks, or announcements.
          </p>

          <div class="compare-pair">
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--bad">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Vague phrasing</span>
              <p>Help me organize this.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Clearer phrasing</span>
              <p>Please read @./data/activity_signup.csv and organize using only this file's contents — don't add anything outside this file.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Or</span>
              <p>Organize based on what the Notion tool returns. Don't assume there are other tasks in Notion that the tool didn't return.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Self-check questions</h4>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>Which <strong>file should the AI read</strong>?</li>
            <li>Is that data <strong>complete</strong>?</li>
            <li>Can the AI <strong>use external information</strong>?</li>
            <li>If <strong>data is missing</strong>, what should the AI do?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Item 3 -->
      <details class="details-card details-card--num">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__num">3</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Has the task been split into steps?</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            Most tasks aren't one-shot. "<strong>Generate an event reminder</strong>" actually contains: read sign-up data, count by session, find missing fields, organize the notes, produce a draft, list items needing human review.
          </p>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            If you just say "<strong>write me an event reminder</strong>", the AI tends to skip the earlier checks and jump straight to plausible-looking text. We'd rather it <strong>walk through the steps</strong>.
          </p>

          <div class="compare-pair">
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">A better phrasing</span>
              <p>
                Please complete in these steps:<br/>
                1. Read the CSV.<br/>
                2. Tally counts for the morning and afternoon sessions.<br/>
                3. Find people whose diet field is blank.<br/>
                4. Produce a reminder draft based on the result.<br/>
                5. End with a list of items needing human review.<br/><br/>
                If the data is incomplete earlier on, stop and don't write a draft.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Self-check questions</h4>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>What <strong>smaller steps</strong> does this break into?</li>
            <li>Which step <strong>has to come first</strong>?</li>
            <li>Which step should <strong>cause a stop on failure</strong>?</li>
            <li>Which steps are <strong>just organizing</strong>, and which <strong>change data</strong>?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Item 4 -->
      <details class="details-card details-card--num">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__num">4</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Which steps actually need a tool?</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            <strong>Not every step needs an MCP tool</strong>. Some steps are just text organization the AI can do on its own. Tools are needed when:
          </p>

          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>Reading Notion tasks</li>
            <li>Creating a Notion page</li>
            <li>Updating Notion status</li>
            <li>Calling an API for data</li>
            <li>Reading a local file</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            <strong>More tools isn't better</strong>. More tools means more risk.
          </p>

          <div class="highlight-card">
            <p class="highlight-text">
              Use a tool when you need <strong>external data</strong>.<br/>
              Use a tool when you need to <strong>create or update data</strong>.<br/>
              For pure <strong>summarizing, classifying, or checking</strong>, you usually <strong>don't need a tool</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="compare-pair">
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">A better phrasing</span>
              <p>Use the notion-classroom tool to read tasks with status「待確認」. After reading, organize the result first — <strong>don't update any tasks yet</strong>.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Or</span>
              <p>Use the weather-api tool to query the weather. If the query succeeds, produce a reminder from the response. <strong>If it fails, stop — don't guess the weather</strong>.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Self-check questions</h4>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>Does this step <strong>really need a tool</strong>?</li>
            <li>Is the AI just organizing text, or does it need <strong>external data</strong>?</li>
            <li>Will the AI <strong>write to or modify data</strong>?</li>
            <li>Is the tool's <strong>permission scope too wide</strong>?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Item 5 -->
      <details class="details-card details-card--num">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__num">5</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Is the output format fixed?</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            If the AI's response shape changes every time, follow-up steps get harder. Sometimes you get a paragraph, sometimes a table, sometimes a long analysis, sometimes the source disappears. <strong>Better to lock the format down up front</strong>.
          </p>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Format example 1: data organization</h4>
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            Please answer in this format:<br/><br/>
            　Data overview:<br/>
            　Issues found:<br/>
            　Basic statistics:<br/>
            　Items needing human review:
          </blockquote>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Format example 2: draft review</h4>
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            Please answer in this format:<br/><br/>
            　Strengths:<br/>
            　Structural issues:<br/>
            　Content issues:<br/>
            　Expression issues:<br/>
            　Suggested revision order:
          </blockquote>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Format example 3: tool execution result</h4>
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            Please answer in this format:<br/><br/>
            　Run status:<br/>
            　Tool used:<br/>
            　Tool response summary:<br/>
            　Success?:<br/>
            　Suggested next step:
          </blockquote>

          <div class="callout-card">
            <p class="callout-text">
              Fixed format means: <strong>humans read it more easily, AI can chain it more easily, and when something goes wrong, it's easier to spot which step failed</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Item 6 -->
      <details class="details-card details-card--num">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__num">6</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Are there stop conditions?</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            A good workflow doesn't always grind to the end. Some situations should trigger a stop:
          </p>

          <ul class="cross-list">
            <li>The data <strong>wasn't provided</strong></li>
            <li>The file <strong>can't be read</strong></li>
            <li>The API <strong>call failed</strong></li>
            <li>Field content is <strong>incomplete</strong></li>
            <li>The user didn't supply a <strong>due date</strong></li>
            <li>The task involves <strong>publishing, sending, deleting, or modifying real data</strong></li>
            <li>The AI <strong>isn't sure which tool to use</strong></li>
          </ul>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            In all these cases, <strong>the AI shouldn't guess</strong>. Add lines like:
          </p>

          <ol class="numbered-list">
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">1</span><span class="numbered-list__text">If <strong>data is incomplete</strong>, stop first and explain what's missing.</span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">2</span><span class="numbered-list__text">If a <strong>tool call fails</strong>, don't fabricate an answer.</span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">3</span><span class="numbered-list__text">If the action involves <strong>publishing, emailing, deleting, or modifying data</strong>, produce a draft first and wait for me to confirm.</span></li>
            <li><span class="numbered-list__num">4</span><span class="numbered-list__text">If you're <strong>unsure which tool to use</strong>, ask first — don't pick on your own.</span></li>
          </ol>

          <div class="callout-card">
            <p class="callout-text">
              Stop conditions don't slow the AI down — they <strong>prevent the AI from acting wrongly when data is missing</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Item 7 -->
      <details class="details-card details-card--num">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__num">7</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">What needs human review?</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            The AI can organize a lot. But some calls still belong to a human:
          </p>

          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>Whether an announcement <strong>can be published</strong></li>
            <li>Whether an email <strong>can be sent</strong></li>
            <li>Whether a Notion status <strong>should really be updated</strong></li>
            <li>Whether to <strong>fill missing data</strong></li>
            <li>Whether a report's stance <strong>matches your own</strong></li>
            <li>Whether a draft <strong>can stand as the final version</strong></li>
            <li>Whether the content involves <strong>private or non-public information</strong></li>
          </ul>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            One simple line at the end of the prompt does a lot of work:
          </p>

          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            At the end, list <strong>items that need human review</strong>.
          </blockquote>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            It pushes the AI from "completing the task" to <strong>"completing the task and flagging risk"</strong>.
          </p>

          <div class="compare-pair">
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Example</span>
              <p>Generate a draft event reminder, but <strong>don't publish it on my behalf</strong>. End with the items that need human review before publishing.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Or</span>
              <p>Help revise the draft, but <strong>don't change the meaning of the original article</strong>. End with items that still need human verification.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Item 8 -->
      <details class="details-card details-card--num">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__num">8</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Does this involve modification or writing?</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            In an AI workflow, <strong>"modify" and "write" need the most caution</strong> — they actually change data: creating a Notion task, updating status, editing a draft, building a page, updating fields. These aren't off-limits, but check first:
          </p>

          <ul class="check-list">
            <li><strong>What's being modified</strong>?</li>
            <li><strong>How wide is the scope</strong>?</li>
            <li>Is the change <strong>reversible</strong>?</li>
            <li>Does it <strong>need human review</strong>?</li>
            <li>Is the AI <strong>only touching the specified fields</strong>?</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="compare-pair">
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--bad">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Vague phrasing</span>
              <p>Just sort it out, and update everything in Notion while you're at it.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">A safer way to ask</span>
              <p>Update only the「狀態」field.<br/>Don't change the task name.<br/>Don't change the due date.<br/>Don't change the notes.<br/>After updating, report the result.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Or</span>
              <p>List the items you intend to update first. <strong>Don't run any update before I confirm</strong>.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Item 9 -->
      <details class="details-card details-card--num">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__num">9</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Does it involve personal or sensitive data?</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            Forms, surveys, sign-up sheets, interview transcripts, course feedback — they often contain personal or sensitive content:
          </p>

          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>Names, emails, phone numbers, student IDs</li>
            <li>Identity information</li>
            <li><strong>Health or dietary needs</strong></li>
            <li>Private opinions</li>
            <li>Interview content</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            This kind of data <strong>shouldn't be casually exposed</strong>, and shouldn't be listed when AI generates public-facing content.
          </p>

          <div class="compare-pair">
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">A better phrasing</span>
              <p>Organize the statistics, but <strong>don't list individual names in the public draft</strong>.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Or</span>
              <p>If names are needed, put them only in the <strong>internal verification list</strong>, not the public draft.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Or</span>
              <p>Check whether the data contains anything inappropriate to publish, and flag it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h4 class="example-heading">Self-check questions</h4>
          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>Does this data contain <strong>personal information</strong>?</li>
            <li>Will the final output <strong>be published publicly</strong>?</li>
            <li>Does it need to be <strong>anonymized</strong>?</li>
            <li>Which content is <strong>internal-only</strong>?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- Item 10 -->
      <details class="details-card details-card--num">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__num">10</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Is the result auditable?</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph">
            A good AI workflow should be <strong>auditable in hindsight</strong>. We should be able to see:
          </p>

          <ul class="check-list">
            <li>What data the AI <strong>used</strong></li>
            <li>What steps the AI <strong>took</strong></li>
            <li>Which parts came <strong>directly from the data</strong></li>
            <li>Which parts are <strong>AI's inference</strong></li>
            <li>Which parts <strong>need human review</strong></li>
          </ul>

          <div class="compare-pair">
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Add lines like</span>
              <p>Mark which content is <strong>derived from the data</strong>, and which is your inference.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Or</span>
              <p>Don't only give the conclusion — also <strong>briefly explain how you got there</strong>.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="compare-pair__item compare-pair__item--good">
              <span class="compare-pair__label">Or</span>
              <p>Anything you're uncertain about, list under "<strong>needs verification</strong>."</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="callout-card">
            <p class="callout-text">
              That way the AI doesn't hand you a result that <strong>looks complete but has unclear origins</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- ============ PART 2: full checklist ============ -->
      <div class="part-divider">
        <span class="part-label">PART 2</span>
        <span class="part-text">Full checklist (10 categories)</span>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        A more complete version. Pull this up before each new AI workflow.
      </p>

      <div class="checklist-group">
        <p class="checklist-group__title">1. Task goal</p>
        <ul class="checklist-group__list">
          <li>I know <strong>what this workflow should ultimately produce</strong>.</li>
          <li>I know <strong>what the final result should look like</strong>.</li>
          <li>I'm <strong>not</strong> using a vague brief like "just sort it out."</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="checklist-group">
        <p class="checklist-group__title">2. Data source</p>
        <ul class="checklist-group__list">
          <li>I've <strong>provided an explicit data source</strong>.</li>
          <li>I've stated whether the AI must <strong>rely only on the named data</strong>.</li>
          <li>I've told the AI to <strong>stop if data is missing</strong>.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="checklist-group">
        <p class="checklist-group__title">3. Step order</p>
        <ul class="checklist-group__list">
          <li>I've <strong>split the task into steps</strong>.</li>
          <li>I've stated <strong>which step comes first</strong>.</li>
          <li>I've stated <strong>which steps cannot be skipped</strong>.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="checklist-group">
        <p class="checklist-group__title">4. Tool use</p>
        <ul class="checklist-group__list">
          <li>I know <strong>which steps actually need a tool</strong>.</li>
          <li>I know which steps are just text organization that <strong>doesn't need a tool</strong>.</li>
          <li>I'm <strong>not letting the AI use unnecessary tools</strong>.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="checklist-group">
        <p class="checklist-group__title">5. Output format</p>
        <ul class="checklist-group__list">
          <li>I've <strong>specified the response format</strong>.</li>
          <li>I've asked for organization in a <strong>table, list, or fixed fields</strong>.</li>
          <li>I'm <strong>not letting the AI vary the format</strong> from run to run.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="checklist-group">
        <p class="checklist-group__title">6. Stop conditions</p>
        <ul class="checklist-group__list">
          <li>I've stated <strong>what to do when a tool fails</strong>.</li>
          <li>I've stated <strong>what to do when data is missing</strong>.</li>
          <li>I've told the AI <strong>not to guess missing data</strong>.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="checklist-group">
        <p class="checklist-group__title">7. Human review</p>
        <ul class="checklist-group__list">
          <li>I've stated <strong>which results need human review</strong>.</li>
          <li>I'm <strong>not</strong> letting the AI publish important content directly.</li>
          <li>I'm <strong>not</strong> letting the AI make high-risk calls on its own.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="checklist-group">
        <p class="checklist-group__title">8. Modification & writing</p>
        <ul class="checklist-group__list">
          <li>If data will be modified, I've <strong>specified the scope of changes</strong>.</li>
          <li>I've asked the AI to <strong>only modify specified fields or drafts</strong>.</li>
          <li>I've <strong>kept the original data or original draft</strong>.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="checklist-group">
        <p class="checklist-group__title">9. Privacy & safety</p>
        <ul class="checklist-group__list">
          <li>I've checked the data for <strong>personal information</strong>.</li>
          <li>I've asked the public version not to <strong>list unnecessary names or details</strong>.</li>
          <li>I'm <strong>not</strong> pasting <strong>API keys, tokens, or passwords</strong> into public content.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="checklist-group">
        <p class="checklist-group__title">10. Result verification</p>
        <ul class="checklist-group__list">
          <li>I've checked whether the AI's response <strong>matches the data</strong>.</li>
          <li>I've confirmed <strong>counts, names, dates, and statuses are correct</strong>.</li>
          <li>I've confirmed the <strong>final result is usable</strong>.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ PART 3: prompt template ============ -->
      <div class="part-divider">
        <span class="part-label">PART 3</span>
        <span class="part-text">A reusable prompt template</span>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If you're not sure where to start, this template works:
      </p>

      <blockquote class="prompt-example prompt-example--template">
        Please complete the task based on the following:<br/><br/>
        <strong>Data source:</strong><br/>
        Read / use ＿＿＿＿＿＿.<br/><br/>
        <strong>Task goal:</strong><br/>
        I want to ＿＿＿＿＿＿.<br/><br/>
        <strong>Steps:</strong><br/>
        1. First ＿＿＿＿＿＿.<br/>
        2. Then ＿＿＿＿＿＿.<br/>
        3. Finally ＿＿＿＿＿＿.<br/><br/>
        <strong>Constraints:</strong><br/>
        1. Use only the named data.<br/>
        2. Don't add anything not in the data.<br/>
        3. If data is missing, stop and explain what's missing.<br/>
        4. If you'd modify, publish, send, or update real data, produce a draft first — don't run the action directly.<br/><br/>
        <strong>Output format:</strong><br/>
        Please answer in this format:<br/><br/>
        　Result:<br/>
        　Data summary:<br/>
        　Items needing verification:<br/>
        　Suggested next step:
      </blockquote>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          You can adapt this template to a lot of cases — organizing CSV, reading articles, reviewing drafts, creating Notion tasks. <strong>All can be derived from this shape</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="detail-heading">Three applied examples</h2>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Example 1: a checked prompt for organizing CSV</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand the full prompt</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            Please read @./data/activity_signup.csv.<br/><br/>
            <strong>Task goal:</strong><br/>
            Organize event sign-up data and surface items needing human review.<br/><br/>
            <strong>Steps:</strong><br/>
            1. Confirm the column names.<br/>
            2. Tally counts for the morning and afternoon sessions.<br/>
            3. Find people whose diet field is blank.<br/>
            4. Produce an internal verification list.<br/><br/>
            <strong>Constraints:</strong><br/>
            1. Use only what's in the CSV.<br/>
            2. Don't fill in answers for blank fields.<br/>
            3. Don't modify the original CSV.<br/>
            4. Don't list every name in any public-facing text.<br/><br/>
            <strong>Output format:</strong><br/>
            　Data overview:<br/>
            　Basic statistics:<br/>
            　Issues found:<br/>
            　Items needing human review:
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Example 2: a checked prompt for driving Notion</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand the full prompt</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <p class="detail-paragraph"><strong>First prompt: read only, no updates</strong></p>
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            Use the notion-classroom tool to list tasks with status「待確認」.<br/><br/>
            <strong>Read only — don't create or update any tasks</strong>.<br/><br/>
            Please answer in this format:<br/><br/>
            　Read status:<br/>
            　Task list:<br/>
            　Suggested priority:<br/>
            　Items needing human review:
          </blockquote>

          <p class="detail-paragraph"><strong>Second prompt: update only after confirmation</strong></p>
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            Please update the given page_id's task status to「處理中」.<br/><br/>
            <strong>Constraints:</strong><br/>
            1. Update only the status.<br/>
            2. Don't change the task name.<br/>
            3. Don't change the due date.<br/>
            4. Don't change the notes.<br/>
            5. Report the result after updating.
          </blockquote>

          <div class="callout-card">
            <p class="callout-text">
              Splitting "<strong>read</strong>" and "<strong>modify</strong>" into separate prompts is safer and easier to audit.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="details-card">
        <summary class="details-card__summary">
          <span class="details-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">▸</span>
          <span class="details-card__title">Example 3: a checked prompt for reading & writing</span>
          <span class="details-card__hint">Click to expand the full prompt</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="details-card__body">
          <blockquote class="prompt-example">
            Please read @./data/article.txt and @./data/assignment.txt.<br/><br/>
            <strong>Task goal:</strong><br/>
            Based on the article and the assignment, generate a reading-report outline.<br/><br/>
            <strong>Constraints:</strong><br/>
            1. Don't write the full report.<br/>
            2. Don't add information not in the article.<br/>
            3. For the personal viewpoint, offer optional directions only — don't decide my stance.<br/>
            4. List anything I still need to confirm myself.<br/><br/>
            <strong>Output format:</strong><br/>
            　Suggested titles:<br/>
            　Article topic:<br/>
            　Section outline:<br/>
            　Optional viewpoint directions:<br/>
            　Items I need to confirm myself:
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- ============ Section: common errors ============ -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Common mistakes</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        A few common patterns when working with AI workflows:
      </p>

      <ul class="role-list">
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label role-item__label--ord">1</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>Task too big.</strong> "Sort the data, write the report, build the Notion page, and update the status — all in one go." Too many steps in one breath: one mistake in the middle and everything downstream is wrong. Better to split it: organize the data first → produce a draft → human review → only then update Notion.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label role-item__label--ord">2</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>No data source named.</strong> The AI fills in content from background knowledge — looks complete, but isn't necessarily true.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label role-item__label--ord">3</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>No stop condition.</strong> When data is missing, the AI keeps writing — and starts guessing.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label role-item__label--ord">4</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>Letting the AI modify real data directly.</strong> Updating, publishing, sending, or deleting without confirmation is high-risk.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label role-item__label--ord">5</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc"><strong>No result verification.</strong> The response reads smoothly, but the <strong>numbers, names, dates, and statuses</strong> can still be wrong.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <!-- ============ Section: when to continue ============ -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">When can the AI move to the next step?</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        A simple rule of thumb:
      </p>

      <ul class="role-list">
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Organize / summarize</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">If it's just <strong>organizing, summarizing, or classifying</strong>, the AI can usually keep going.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Produce a draft</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">Can keep going, but <strong>label it as a draft</strong>.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Modify data</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">Confirm the <strong>scope of modification</strong> first.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="role-item">
          <span class="role-item__label">Publish / write</span>
          <span class="role-item__desc">If it involves <strong>publishing, sending, deleting, or updating real data</strong>, get <strong>human confirmation first</strong>.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          <strong>Organizing can move fast.</strong><br/>
          <strong>Drafts need confirmation.</strong><br/>
          <strong>Modifications stay narrow.</strong><br/>
          <strong>Publishing is a human call.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- ============ Section: takeaway ============ -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">The most important idea on this page</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        AI workflows aren't <strong>"hand everything to AI."</strong> They're about splitting the task clearly so the AI can help inside a <strong>clear, safe, auditable</strong> boundary. Before each workflow, confirm:
      </p>

      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>What's the <strong>goal</strong></li>
        <li>Where does the <strong>data come from</strong></li>
        <li>What's the <strong>step order</strong></li>
        <li>Where do you <strong>need a tool</strong></li>
        <li>Should it <strong>stop on failure</strong></li>
        <li>Which results <strong>need human review</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        AI is good at <strong>repetition, organization, checking, drafts, and first-pass suggestions</strong>. But <strong>important calls still belong to a human</strong>.
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card highlight-card--final">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          Data sources clear. Tool permissions limited.<br/>
          Output format fixed. Stop on failure.<br/>
          <strong>Important actions stay with a human.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

